{"cursor":"5980","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In zoology, a 'folivore' is a herbivore that specializes in eating leaves.\nMature leaves contain a high proportion of hard-to-digest cellulose, less energy\nthan other types of foods, and often toxic compounds. Jones, S., Martin, R., & Pilbeam, D. (1994) The\nCambridge Encyclopedia of Human Evolution. Cambridge: Cambridge University\nPress For this reason folivorous animals tend to have long digestive\ntracts and slow metabolisms. Many enlist the help of symbiotic bacteria to\nrelease the nutrients in their diet. Additionally, as has been observed in\nfolivorous primates, animals may exhibit a strong preference for immature\nleaves, which tend to be higher in energy and protein and lower in fibre and\npoisons than more mature leaves.\n","linknr":255,"url":"Folivore","recorded":1362482845,"links":29,"instances":["zoology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Herbivory","Folivores|"],"headings":["Evolution","Folivory and flight","Arboreal folivores","Primates","Examples","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Opisthocomus_hoazin.jpg/220px-Opisthocomus_hoazin.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Bradypus.jpg/220px-Bradypus.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c9/Alouatta-caraya_ppia-m01b.jpg/220px-Alouatta-caraya_ppia-m01b.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Okapi2.jpg/220px-Okapi2.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Starling_Feeding_Offspring.jpg/160px-Starl